 instantiations of civil society, all the authors nonetheless take seriously the potential inherent in civil society, particularly as it comes to influence global politics. They demand, however, an expansion of both the concept and project of civil society in order to make its political opportunities available to all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCivil societyxHistoryvCongresses. 0aCivil societyxHistory. 0aFeminist theoryvCongresses. 0aFeminist theory. 0aPolitical science. 0aSocial sciences. 0aWomen's rightsxHistoryvCongresses. 0aWomen's rightsxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBudde, Gunilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudde, Gunilla, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Belinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGailus, Manfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhodsee, Kristen R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsborg, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagemann, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagemann, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLake, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMettele, Gisela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichel, Sonya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichel, Sonya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOffen, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPernau, Margrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRendall, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary